modules.title: TWITTER THREAD FROM MINNESOTA NATIONAL GUARD

nib.text:
Shots were fired at a team of Minnesota National Guard members and Minneapolis Police officers early Sunday morning in Willard-Hay, officials say. 

At 4:20 a.m. MPD officers and Minnesota National Guard members were providing neighborhood security near West Broadway Avenue and North Penn Avenue when a white or light-colored SUV approached and a passenger fired shots. 

Officers at the scene estimated ten gunshots were fired. 

One National Guard member with lacerations from shattered glass was transported to an area hospital. 

A second National Guard member sustained minor injuries. 

No officers were struck by the gunfire or seriously injured, officials told local news sources.

nib.text:
An argument turned deadly when a man fell during an altercation on the front steps of a bar near Irvine Park on Saturday.

Emergency personnel responded to multiple reports of a man assaulted on the 300 block of Washington Street around 11:35 p.m.

Officers arrived to find a 48-year-old man still on the ground, suffering from a head injury.

Medics transported the man to an area hospital in critical condition.

According to a tweet from the Saint Paul PD, the man died from his injuries around 3 p.m. on Sunday.

The Ramsey County Medical Examinerâs Office is conducting an autopsy to determine an exact cause of death.

The other man involved in the fight has been identified since fleeing the scene Saturday night.

The investigation remains open and active. No arrests have been made.

* Those seeking medical care
* Those experiencing homelessness
* Members of the media 
* Emergency responders including law enforcement and medical services.

Crowds gathered outside the Brooklyn Center Police Department for the seventh consecutive night Saturday as demonstrators called for justice in the shooting of Daunte Wright.

After 136 arrests were made the previous night, Brooklyn Center Mayor Mike Elliott issued a citywide curfew from 11 p.m. Saturday night to 6 a.m. Sunday morning. 

According to [KARE 11 news](https://www.kare11.com/article/news/local/daunte-wright/day-seven-after-daunte-wrights-death-protest/89-028efeaf-7265-43b4-b399-335a5a29dfc1), Saturday's demonstrations began with a church group holding a sing-a-long outside the Brooklyn Center Police Department. 

The crowdâwhich reportedly included Representative Maxine Waters and Reverend Jesse Jackson, Sr.âcontinued to grow outside the police station continued to grow as the night went on. 

Less than 30 minutes before the curfew went into effect, over 300 protesters were estimated to still remain in the area, and approximately 100 people continued to demonstrate after the curfew began, according to the Minnesota Operation Safety Net.

Police were reportedly [requested not to use](https://www.mprnews.org/story/2021/04/17/protests-continue-in-brooklyn-center-for-a-seventh-night) means such as tear gas and rubber bullets to enforce the curfew. 

In total, one arrest was made Saturday night.
